<doc docid="groups.google.com_fwcc_f363bceb6bd8a406_CMN_20060215_082900" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E01">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Mom Ten Years Ago </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Helen Li </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> I saw this article and want to share it with you. </seg>
<seg id="4"> This is not out of a momentary impulse but of warmth and kindness cherished long at heart. </seg>
<seg id="5"> I asked myself how I would act if it were me. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The answer was very clear.  I would put down the phone with a "You dialed a wrong number." </seg>
<seg id="7"> I have been thinking this year what exactly can be considered helping others. </seg>
<seg id="8"> I have already given up those momentary actions such as making monetary or material donations. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Two days ago, a friend said, I have already no time to take care of myself.  Even if I want to help others, I will not have the energy to do it. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Wish you a pleasant day :) </seg>
<seg id="11"> Helen </seg>
<seg id="12"> Mom Ten Years Ago </seg>
<seg id="13"> On that day ten years ago, when this teacher was taking a nap at home during noontime break, the telephone rang suddenly. </seg>
<seg id="14"> She picked up the phone and listened, yet out came a strange rough voice: "We have caught your kid stealing a book.  Come here quick!" </seg>
<seg id="15"> Coming from the other end of the line was a little girl's cryingï¼ along with loud scolding voices of others. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Glancing over at her only daughter, who was watching TV nearby, it suddenly dawned upon her. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Obviously, a little girl must have got caught by the sales person while she was stealing a book.  As she did not want to let her family know it, she must have made up a phone number at random.  That was how they happened to call here. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Of course she could put down the phone and ignored the call.  She could also even reprimand the other party, </seg>
<seg id="19"> because this incident had nothing to do with her. </seg>
<seg id="20"> However, being a teacher, she thought she might be her own student. </seg>
<seg id="21"> The phone call gave her some rough idea that the little girl, who made the momentary slip, must be very much frightened and was facing perhaps the most horrifying situation in her life. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Hesitating for a moment, an idea suddenly occurred to her.  Right, just do it this way. </seg>
<seg id="23"> So, after making sure about the bookstore's address, she hurried there. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Just as she expected, a tearful little girl was standing in the bookstore, </seg>
<seg id="25"> while adults nearby were yelling at her in fierce reproof. </seg>
<seg id="26"> She rushed up to hold the poor little girl in her arms.  Turning around, she said to the sales person nearby: "Talk to me.  Don't scare the kid." </seg>
<seg id="27"> Amid the sales person's reluctant mutterings, she paid the fine of about a few dozen yuan before she was able to lead this little girl out of the bookstore and take a close look at that tear-smudged, terrified face. </seg>
<seg id="28"> She laughed and took the little girl home.  She gave her a good cleaning and let the girl go without asking anything. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Before she took off, she made a special effort to tell her repeatedly, if you want to read books, just come to the auntie's place.  There are many books inside. </seg>
<seg id="30"> The little girl, who had still not yet recovered from her horror, took a close look at her and scampered away.  She never reappeared. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Time went by like a rushing stream.  Ten years had passed in a flash before she knew it. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Having long forgotten this thing, she still lived here, leading a quiet and peaceful life. </seg>
<seg id="33"> One day at noon, there was a series of knocks on the door. </seg>
<seg id="34"> When she opened the door, she saw a stranger, a pretty young girl with all smiles on her face and her hands full of gifts. </seg>
<seg id="35"> "Who are you looking for?" </seg>
<seg id="36"> She asked doubtfully. </seg>
<seg id="37"> In her excitement, that girl said a great deal. </seg>
<seg id="38"> Only with great efforts in following the narration of that girl, a stranger to her, did she suddenly realize that she was that little girl of that year.  She had graduated smoothly from college after ten years and now took this trip purposely to visit her. </seg>
<seg id="39"> With her eyes glistening with tears, the young girl said softly: "Though I have never understood even today why you were willing to pretend to be my mom to help me out, I have always felt all these ten years that I want to call you mom." </seg>
<seg id="40"> The teacher's eyes also grew blurry. </seg>
<seg id="41"> She asked curiously: "If I had not helped you, what would have happened?" </seg>
<seg id="42"> The girl's face immediately darkened.  She gently shook her head and said: "I am not sure.  I could have done something foolish and might have even committed suicide." </seg>
<seg id="43"> The teacher's heart trembled, and she started to feel rejoiced secretly. </seg>
<seg id="44"> The decision she made on the spur of the moment that year turned out to have had such an impact on one person's life. </seg>
<seg id="45"> Looking at the happy smile on the girl's face, she also smiled. </seg>
<poster>
<seg id="46"> Zhang xiwen </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="47"> When this world is filled with lies and fraud like junk text messages everywhere, Buddha said, if I don't go to hell, who else goes to hell. </seg>
<seg id="48"> If anyone has done this, then congratulations, because he could become Buddha earlier. </seg>
<seg id="49"> Human beings at their birth are naturally good. </seg>
<seg id="50"> Compassion lies in the heart of every human being. </seg>
<seg id="51"> The moral degeneration of the world is getting worse day by day.  People are not what they were in times past. </seg>
<seg id="52"> Perhaps only self-sacrificing Buddha can do some good deeds. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_goodarticles_90837c9a1fbe858e_CMN_20060214_082900" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E01">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Observation on Military Situation: How Long Would Iran be Able to Hold on Against US Military Air Strikes? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Yun Feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> If we liken a traditional war of attrition to making the enemy bleed to death, then modern warfare is firing a bullet right into the enemy's head at the outset, turning it into a "vegetable" with no time to bleed. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The difference between Iran and the US in military power is not in the numbers but in their understanding of modern warfare. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Iran, which fought an eight-year war with Iraq without any distinguishable winner, does not seem to understand the real significance of modern high-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The British International Intelligence Review recently mentioned, after analyzing US military deployments, that US troops are preparing to launch a large-scale air strike on Iran... </seg>
<seg id="7"> The current status of the Iranian Air Force is rather worrisome. </seg>
<seg id="8"> The current status of the Iranian Air Force is very similar to the pre-war Iraqi Air Force in 2003. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The home country does not have the ability to develop modern weapons independently and is also under the arms embargo imposed by the West. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Upon the breakout of war, it is quite uncertain whether the old and outdated planes of the Iranian Air Force could take off and fight the US military. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Currently, Iran's air defense system is chiefly composed of the air force and land-based air defense force of Iran's regular military as well as the air defense force of the Revolutionary Guard Corps. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Among these, the Iranian Air Force is currently about 50,000 strong and has more than 300 fighter planes of various models. </seg>
<seg id="13"> The main plane models are US-made F-4 Phantoms, F-5 Tigers, and F-14 Tomcats, and Russian-made MIG-29s, among others. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The land-based air defense forces are mainly equipped with US-made Hawk, British-made Arrow, and some Russian-made Sam series surface-to-air missiles. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Analyzing the current status of the Iranian air defense forces, Harold Hutchinson, a US military expert, Khramchikhin, a military expert at Russia's Institute of Political and Military Analysis, and others think that looking at the current situation, there are still some holes in Iran's air defense capabilities and its air defense system construction. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Hutchinson thinks that in terms of overall real power, the Iranian Air Force is absolutely not at the same level as the US military. </seg>
<seg id="17"> The large number of US-made fighter planes Iran has are inoperable due to lack of spare parts, upgrades, and maintenance. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Of the F-14 fighters, once considered the trump of the Iranian Air Force, currently only 10-plus can take off. </seg>
<seg id="19"> It is also questionable whether the AIM-54 Phoenix missiles that they carry, which are said to have over-the-horizon attack capability, are reliable in actual battle. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Khramchikhin mentioned that the air defense missile systems that the US provided to Iran in the 1970s and 1980s have lost combat power due to lack of spare parts. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Some other non-system air defense weapons acquired from Russia and other countries are no match for the US military, which is capable of electromagnetic countermeasures. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Scraping it together has an effect on combat power. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The Iranian government obviously also realizes that its fate in war depends on its ability to defend the home skies.  In a last-minute effort to update its weaponry, it scraped together all it could get to reinforce its air defense system. </seg>
<seg id="24"> From what can be seen at present, its methods can be summarized into two. </seg>
<seg id="25"> First, work hard to conceal key nuclear facilities to enhance its capability to defend against attacks. </seg>
<seg id="26"> According to a report by the British newspaper the Times, Iran has concealed the core parts of nuclear facilities such as the Natanz nuclear plant and Isfahan uranium enrichment center as deep as 18 meters underground and encased them with 2-meter thick cement protection. </seg>
<seg id="27"> However, the US military is a step ahead, having seen the effects of underground bunkers during the 1991 Gulf war in defending against air strikes, it rushed development of various kinds of ground penetrating bombs. </seg>
<seg id="28"> After more than ten years of targeted research, the US military now has a complete package of combat methodology and weapons to deal with reinforced underground bunkers. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Iran has recently also bought large quantities of air defense weaponry from Russia. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Since the end of last year, the Iranian government has made successive agreements with Russia to purchase the Pechora-2A air defense missile system, along with 29 sets of the Tor-M1 air defense missile system worth 700 million US dollars. </seg>
<seg id="31"> However, modern warfare is a competition between systems. </seg>
<seg id="32"> The various air strike weapons of the US military were all developed independently by their own country.  Furthermore, after years of real war experience, they have been adapted into a set of impressive and effective war machines. </seg>
<seg id="33"> In contrast, whether the "new weapons" Iran gathered from other countries and put together can become a combat force within such short period of time is still an issue. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Iran is not lagging behind in weapons only. </seg>
<seg id="35"> The Army Field Manual published by the US military in 1982 proposed for the first time the doctrine of "Air Land Battle," which emphasizes attacking the enemy's deeply strategic and high-value targets using air superiority to paralyze the enemy's command system at the start of the war so that the enemy can become nothing more than "meat on the chopping board" no matter how powerful its regular military strength. </seg>
<seg id="36"> In the 1991 Gulf War, the 1999 Kosovo War, and the 2003 Iraq War, the US military cared not about how many planes the enemy had but the range of its own Tomahawk cruise missiles. </seg>
<seg id="37"> Although the Iranian government has been preparing for possible air strikes and has started taking measures to enhance its air defense capabilities, Iran, which fought an eight-year war with Iraq without any distinguishable winner, does not seem to understand the real significance of modern high-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="38"> Along with the US military's progress in recent years in military transformation work, the US military's air strike operations already completely differ from Vietnam War era carpet bombing, depending instead on various kinds of high-tech weapons and on modern information technology-based high precision and full depth air attacks. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Confronted with such air strikes, it is still unknown how long Iran's land-based air defense system would be able to hold on. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Source: CRI Online - "World News Journal" </seg>
