<doc docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_a6b18a4b27644df8_CMN_20060215_083500" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E01">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Dalai's Special Envoys Meet with Chinese Officials behind Closed Doors </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> CGP Beili </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Dalai's special envoys meet with Chinese officials behind closed doors. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The Dalai Lama stressed that he wants autonomy, not independence, for Tibet. </seg>
<seg id="5"> The special envoys of the Dalai Lama, Tibet's spiritual leader in exile, are having closed-door meetings with Chinese officials in Beijing with no details released. </seg>
<seg id="6"> This is the fifth official meeting between China and the Dalai's government-in-exile since contacts resumed in 2002. </seg>
<seg id="7"> However, as always, the two sides met behind close doors with no details revealed. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Reporters said that the two sides held talks several times but so far no substantive results have been achieved. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The Dalai Lama, who is in exile in northern India, said that he wants autonomy, not independence, for Tibet. </seg>
<seg id="10"> The Chinese side refused to comment on the bilateral talks. </seg>
<seg id="11"> However, analysts said that Beijing wanted to have the dialogue partly because it is worried that Tibetans' dissatisfaction with the Chinese rule may escalate should this 70-year-old spiritual leader in exile die. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Cultural Identity </seg>
<seg id="13"> The delegation of Dalai's government-in-exile was led by Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari, who was also chief representative to several previous talks. </seg>
<seg id="14"> A spokesperson for the Tibetan government-in-exile said that the several rounds of talks they had with Chinese officials in Switzerland in 2005 were very "close and frank," bringing hopes for Tibetans. </seg>
<seg id="15"> The spokesperson said that their ultimate hope is to resolve the relevant issues on the basis reached through negotiation with the Chinese leadership so that Tibetans will have the freedom to preserve their cultural identity, which they consider important. </seg>
<poster>
<seg id="16"> CGP Beili </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="17"> Dalai Lama's Special Envoys Reiterate they do not Seek Tibet's Independence. </seg>
<seg id="18"> The Dalai Lama will go to visit Washington this month. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Prior to the Tibetan spiritual leader Dalai Lama's visit to the United States on November 8, his special envoys said that the Tibetan government-in-exile would not demand for Tibet's independence. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said in Washington that he hoped the Chinese government would indeed preserve Tibet's unique culture and tradition. </seg>
<seg id="21"> During his visit to the US next week, the Dalai Lama is expected to discuss the Tibetan issue with President Bush in hopes that Bush can urge the Chinese government to give Tibet genuine autonomy. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Dalai's representative had direct contact with Beijing officials for the first time in Berne in July of this year. </seg>
<seg id="23"> "Genuine Autonomy" </seg>
<seg id="24"> Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari noted that in recent years the Tibetan government-in-exile has seen some positive aspects when meeting with Chinese authorities. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The Dalai Lama's special envoys found that Beijing leaders, especially the representatives from the United Front Work Department of the CPC Central Committee, were more willing than before to hear their opinions. </seg>
<seg id="26"> However, Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari said that the Tibetan government-in-exile still has too many disagreements with the Chinese government and that there is a very big difference between the positions of the two sides. </seg>
<seg id="27"> He said that during the past five years the Tibetan government-in-exile has tried its best to meet the Chinese request for creating a good negotiation environment. </seg>
<seg id="28"> China should also create a good environment for negotiations on the Tibetan issue instead of suppressing the Dalai Lama unrelentingly. </seg>
<seg id="29"> He said that the Dalai Lama does not demand independence for Tibet.  Tibet is still part of China, but the Chinese government must preserve Tibet's unique culture so that "Tibetans will have genuine autonomy." </seg>
<seg id="30"> In addition, Lodi Gyaltsen Gyari noted that some Chinese think the Tibetan issue will disappear once the Dalai Lama dies. </seg>
<seg id="31"> He said that this idea is very dangerous because China will lose a historic opportunity to solve the Tibetan issue once the Dalai Lama passes away. </seg>
<seg id="32"> He said that as long as the Chinese government responds to the requests of the Dalai Lama and proposes a final resolution, the Dalai Lama will not need to talk about the Tibetan issue internationally. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b07aeae684cbc1b7_CMN_20060209_051800" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E01">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Negotiation And Compromise are Important Democratic Methods! (ZT) </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Houze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> I just saw a post by a net friend on The Great Spirit: To Old Mr. Guiren. </seg>
<seg id="4"> His/her original words were "negotiation and compromise are important democratic methods, or else, splitting because of disagreements is the failure of democracy!!!  I hope idealistic democrats will pay full attention to this point!" </seg>
<seg id="5"> This bland remark that has not roused interest among any net friends led me to indulge in a train of thought while all sorts of feelings welled up in my mind. </seg>
<seg id="6"> At this time, I thought of ancient China as well as the past of the West. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Seldom posting topics, I could not help replying to the post of this net friend in the form of a topic post. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Let's take a look first at ancient China. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Everybody knows that beginning with the First Qin Emperor, China has constructed a large and unified centralized power system, with all dynasties that followed operating under this political framework. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Although a "double-track system" was temporarily implemented in the Han Dynasty, that is, a political system consisting of a dual coexisting feudal system and centralized power system, after all, there was still a centralized power system in the end. </seg>
<seg id="11"> The effect of this kind of centralized power system under the conditions at that time in history had its progressive side, had its aspect of promoting the development of forces of production. </seg>
<seg id="12"> However, we should also see that the prolonged period of more than 2,000 years of running this system resulted in a lack of creativity, initiative, and activity in local areas, making it even less possible to formulate, based on local conditions, various kinds of regulations and policies appropriate for local development. </seg>
<seg id="13"> The pyramid-like system of government also caused lower-level officials to only look upward, following every detail of orders from higher levels. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Since all local officials in the county government were appointed by the central government, they had no room for coordination and negotiation among themselves, let alone with those ordinary citizens. </seg>
<seg id="15"> When their rights were infringed upon, peasants in ancient China could do nothing but put up with it time and again. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Only when their most basic rights were threatened, that is, when their rights of existence were deprived by widespread famine, tyranny, and natural disasters, would they rise in revolt with sharpened sticks. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Over 2,000 years, several peasant uprisings spread like storms across the country, from the spontaneous Chen Sheng Wu Guang Uprising to the plotted Yellow Turban Uprising, to the Huang Chao Riot in the Tang Dynasty, as well as the one-month dynastic rule as a result of Li Zicheng's uprising.  Except for Zhu Yuanzhang, none achieved victory in the true sense of the word. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Even the Ming Dynasty established this way by Zhu Yuanzhang was still nothing but a rotating replacement of other dynasties, with no change in the system. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Born a commoner with little education, Zhu Yuanzhang implemented ancient China's centralized power system to a sickening extreme.  The brimming vitality characteristic of the Tang Dynasty, born of openness, freedom, and tolerance, was replaced by stagnant lifelessness. </seg>
<seg id="20"> The free speech atmosphere vanished from the land of China for some time. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Human nature suffered utmost suppression. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Everyone became overcautious and dared not talk too much, from fear and trepidation. </seg>
<seg id="23"> The result of this sole successful peasant uprising over 2,000 years turned the Chinese people into subhuman beings for a period of time. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Now let's take a look at the Middle Ages in Western Europe, known as the Dark Ages. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The Middle Ages in Western Europe was a period of one thousand years which came about after Western Rome was destroyed by nomads and had nothing to do with the previous ancient Greece and Rome. </seg>
<seg id="26"> This period was characterized by fiefdoms, namely land fiefdoms. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Landlords at lower levels had more independent power. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Whether they were small feudal lords with territories extending a few kilometers or the nobility of dukes, marquises, counts, viscounts, and barons who appeared on formal occasions, as people of various ranks were able to mutually check and balance and depend on one another, with the conditions and abilities to fight for their legitimate rights from the king, there were scenes of kings and noblemen sitting together for negotiations of their own respective interests, scenes never seen in ancient Chinese history. </seg>
<seg id="29"> They made mutual compromises and concessions instead of overthrowing or superseding other parties by using force. </seg>
<seg id="30"> This way, by means of various kinds of contracts, rights were continuously granted to noblemen and commoners, and with increasing power for noblemen and commoners, the king's rights became increasingly diminished. </seg>
<seg id="31"> In the end, the British queen became only ceremonial, with no actual power. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Democracy was gradually realized through this method! </seg>
<seg id="33"> Let's come back to make a comparison with ancient China, with all power centralized in the hands of the emperor (except for Li Shimin) and with almost no noblemen.  It would be hard for peasants to sit with the king at the negotiating table over a cup of tea and a glass of wine, making mutual compromises and concessions in a relaxed and pleasant manner and formulating contracts to the satisfaction of the two sides. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Under such circumstances, when the right of existence was deprived, the only way remaining was to overthrow the existing dynasty by force and try to replace it. </seg>
<seg id="35"> Consequently, there was a repeated rotation, from the heyday of the Tang Dynasty to the morbidity of the Ming Dynasty. </seg>
<seg id="36"> Comparing Chinese history with Western history, we find there seems to be no Western country where conflict between the ruler and the ruled was as aggravated as it was in ancient China. </seg>
<seg id="37"> In no Western country were peasant uprisings as frequent as in ancient China. </seg>
<seg id="38"> In Western countries, when conflicts between ancient royal households and peasants arose, noblemen and commoners would first think of achieving resolution through negotiations to protect their own interests.  They would make some mutual concessions to gradually win more rights, while force was rarely used. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Understanding this, you will see that even as we enter the 21st century, some democratic "fighters" on the internet, having inherited the idea of the ultra, absolute totalitarian system of the Ming Dynasty, </seg>
<seg id="40"> and also because their bodies are eroded by the poison of the Cultural Revolution, these democratic "fighters" can talk about nothing except annihilation and overthrow. </seg>
<seg id="41"> Yet it is this kind of ideology that is the largest obstacle to democracy, because these people don't understand that negotiation, consultation, and compromise are the most important methods and approaches for realizing democracy. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_b1314fab782e7592_CMN_20060209_044700" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E01">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> Cao Xiaoming: Who Foots Bill for Enriching Rural Cultural Activities? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> Houze </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> This Spring Festival, this writer was lucky enough to spend the holiday in rural China and visit some relatives and friends. </seg>
<seg id="4"> While impressed by the rich festive atmosphere in rural China, I was also concerned with the drab cultural activities in the countryside. </seg>
<seg id="5"> This writer found in one village with friends and relatives that previously at Spring Festival each year, this village would spontaneously organize villagers to put on a local theatrical show called "Revolving Lantern." </seg>
<seg id="6"> Both adults and children could play roles in this show based on characters in the Three Warring Kingdoms.  The villagers never grew tired of watching it. </seg>
<seg id="7"> There were several performing teams for "Revolving Lantern" across the township.  They not only performed in their own villages but also visited other villages, creating liveliness through their exchanges. </seg>
<seg id="8"> However, this year this village no longer organized it. </seg>
<seg id="9"> It turned out that a large sum of money was needed for purchasing costumes alone for "Revolving Lantern."  In the past, costumes were bought through fund raising among the villagers, yet they are now too worn out to wear. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Asking villagers door to door for money again, nobody wanted to do it.  Similar situations also occurred in several other villages across the township. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Without the "Revolving Lantern," the village suddenly became cold and cheerless. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Adults started to play mahjong. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Children also started to play poker. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Villagers all said there was nothing going on for this New Year festival. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Setting off firecrackers or playing mahjong has now become one of the major features of the New Year celebration in rural areas. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Meanwhile, gambling persists in spite of numerous bans and is tending to spread further.  Winning or losing as much as 10,000 yuan in a single game has even become commonplace.  In particular, a large number of peasants returning from their migrant jobs outside have become major players at gambling houses. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Their money earned by their own sweat over a whole year thereby goes down the drain. </seg>
<seg id="18"> In addition, gambling-related family disputes frequently occur.  Some even lead to tragedies of divorce and death. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Some peasants say they gamble not only during the New Year festival, but also frequently participate in gambling during the slack season. </seg>
<seg id="20"> There is no place to go if they don't gamble. </seg>
<seg id="21"> It is too difficult to organize some cultural activities, to find some fun in rural areas. </seg>
<seg id="22"> There are neither facilities nor funds, but also there are no people acting as organizers. </seg>
<seg id="23"> However, in this regard, what Jiangxi has done is doubtlessly good news for peasants. </seg>
<seg id="24"> In order to enrich the cultural life of the peasant population, the Jiangxi provincial government, starting in September of last year, not only implemented "theatrical performances funded by the government, operated by the market, supported by townships, provided for peasant enjoyment," </seg>
<seg id="25"> but is also allocating at least 60 million yuan annually to a special fund for rural cultural enterprises, so as to bring high-quality cultural products to the rural population. </seg>
<seg id="26"> At the start of the new year, 10 million yuan was again added, bringing the total amount to 100 million yuan for the establishment of the special fund for rural cultural enterprise. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Moreover, the "bills" paid with this special fund are for real benefits: </seg>
<seg id="28"> inviting various kinds of professional artistic troupes to stage performances in rural areas, with at least four performances per year in each township; </seg>
<seg id="29"> inviting various movie theater companies to dispatch teams to put on movies in rural areas, with at least six dramas and educational science movies per year in each administrative village; </seg>
<seg id="30"> organizing and carrying out mass cultural activities with local characteristics, with at least 2-3 events per year in each township. </seg>
<seg id="31"> From this "purchase inventory list," it is easy for us to see that the government is not simply providing funds, but trying its best to think about how to use the limited funding to provide what is most needed and to bring value-added cultural enjoyment for the vast rural population.  It has done a real job. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Currently, the vast numbers of peasants are rejoicing about being exempt from paying grain tax to the government. </seg>
<seg id="33"> If the government can do what Jiangxi did to "foot the bill" for enriching rural people's cultural activities, it will be another joy from heaven for peasants. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Furthermore, this "joy" will not only get peasants away from the mahjong table but also get them "active" in cultural activities, which helps add contributions to the construction of new socialist rural areas. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_greenpartycn_d6c87f9f9950da31_CMN_20060214_106700" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E01">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> False Alarm: Wang Peirong's Child Almost Got Kidnapped </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> peirongwangsohu@gmail.com </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Wang Peirong's child almost got kidnapped, but it turned out to be a false alarm. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Some time after 9:00 p.m. on January 24, 2006, Wang Peirong's child gave a full account: </seg>
<seg id="5"> On the morning of January 24, 2006, Wang Peirong's child was called out by the entrance guard when she was attending a make-up class in physics in the Xuzhou No. 3 Middle School. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The entrance guard told Wang Peirong's child that three unidentified men said to the No. 3 Middle School entrance guard, Wang Peirong's child Wang Tianjiao has not been home for three days due to her parents' quarrel. </seg>
<seg id="7"> Now her mother has disappeared.  As we are the leaders at her mother's workplace, we want to go inside the No. 3 Middle School to take away Wang Peirong's child. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Wang Peirong's child said to the entrance guard that what these three men said were all lies, and she refused to go with these three men. </seg>
<seg id="9"> With the help of the No. 3 Middle School entrance guard, Wang Peirong's child was not taken away. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Wang Peirong's child called her mother's leader at noon to investigate this incident, and that leader denied having sent anyone to the Xuzhou No. 3 Middle School. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Wang Peirong's child got her father's leader's telephone number from her. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Wang Peirong's child called her father's leader. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Wang Peirong's child said: "Three people came to the No. 3 Middle Scholl and wanted to take me away." </seg>
<seg id="14"> That leader asked: "Why didn't you go with them?" </seg>
<seg id="15"> Wang Peirong's child answered: "I will surely die if I go with them." </seg>
<seg id="16"> After saying that, Wang Peirong's child hung up the phone. </seg>
<seg id="17"> After hearing what Wang Peirong's child said, Wang Peirong felt it was a serious case and reported it to police. </seg>
<seg id="18"> On January 25, the feedback from the police station was that what Wang Peirong's child had said was basically true. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The police station asked the security department of the China University of Mining and Technology whether it had sent anyone to find Wang Peirong's child at the No. 3 Middle School.  The answer was no. </seg>
<seg id="20"> The police station again asked the CUMT security department whether the work unit affiliated with CUMT had sent anyone to find Wang Peirong's child at the No. 3 Middle School.  The answer was another no. </seg>
<seg id="21"> The relevant department asked others to tell Wang Peirong and his family to pay attention to their safety. </seg>
<seg id="22"> After the incident, the leaders of the relevant departments in Xuzhou City took it seriously. </seg>
<seg id="23"> Through the criminal investigation department of the Xuzhou Municipal Public Security Bureau, the possibility of child kidnapping was ruled out. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Wang Peirong thanked the leaders of the relevant departments in Xuzhou City as well as the criminal investigation department of the Xuzhou Municipal Public Security Bureau. </seg>
<seg id="25"> This was a false alarm, and the false alarm was probably caused mainly by the No. 3 Middle School entrance guard. </seg>
<seg id="26"> The criminal investigation department of the Xuzhou Municipal Public Security Bureau has now confirmed:  On January 24, three people including the leader from the School of Science, Wang Peirong's workplace, could not find Wang Peirong by phone.  As they urgently needed to find Wang Peirong (Wang Peirong has so far no idea what that was about), they thought of going to the No. 3 Middle School to find the teacher of Wang Peirong's child so as to ask whether the child was in Xuzhou. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Heavy Topics:  Why is There Lower Risk to Engage in Corruption while cost of Anti-corruption is Higher? </seg>
<seg id="28"> http://bbs.people.com.cn/bbs/ReadFile?whichfile=44796&typeid=39 </seg>
<seg id="29"> With the current cadre mechanism and the anti-corruption mechanism, a corrupt official need only worry about a handful of relevant officials who supervise him rather than the vast majority of the masses. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Therefore, once he thinks he has successfully hoodwinked or balanced those few officials who can control his fate, he will feel safe in carrying out his great cause of corruption and wealth accumulation unscrupulously and at will,  disregarding how the people close to him feel. </seg>
<seg id="31"> In contrast, when ordinary people with no power in their hands take the lead in combating corruption at the sight of an injustice, they may likely be met with extremely cruel retaliation and revenge. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Or they may be also politically labeled against and may anytime suffer the fate of dying before the battle has won. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Comparing the two: those who practice corruption take less risk while those who combat corruption bear the high cost instead. </seg>
<seg id="34"> For full article, please see http://bbs.people.com.cn/bbs/ReadFile?whichfile=44796&typeid=39 </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="CCTV4_DAILYNEWS_CMN_20060207_145800_396_582.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="E02">
<seg id="1"> Now let's look at Iran's nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="2"> The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) confirmed on the 6th that the Iranian government had written to the agency requesting the removal of all equipments that monitor Iran's nuclear facilities by the middle of the month. </seg>
<seg id="3"> Since the IAEA decided to report Iran's nuclear issue to the UN Security Council, Iran had announced the termination of all supportive and cooperative measures it had adopted in the nuclear issue, and refused to allow the IAEA to conduct any further surprise inspections of its nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Speaking on the tension in Iran's nuclear issue, Russia's Foreign Minister Lavrov stated in Athens, Greece, on the 6th that the collaboration between Russia and Iran still exists. </seg>
<seg id="5"> This will be the driving force in resolving Iran's nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="6"> A spokesman for Russia's Ministry of Foreign Affairs claimed on the same day that Russia's proposal to Iran on building a joint uranium enrichment enterprise in Russia is still effective. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The two parties may hold discussions on this issue next week. </seg>
<seg id="8"> On the same day, Lugar, the U.S. Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman, indicated at the UN Headquarters in New York that the United States disagreed with Israel's attack on Iran's nuclear facilities. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Recent reports claimed that Israeli defense experts said that the Israeli air force may deliver a heavy blow to Iran's nuclear facilities if necessary. </seg>
<seg id="10"> The Xinhua News Agency reported that Kislyak, Russia's Deputy Foreign Minister, stated on the 7th that Russia is willing to cooperate with Iran on the nuclear issue, assisting Iran to obtain the legitimate right to peacefully develop nuclear power. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Kislyak said that Russia's proposal on a joint uranium enrichment enterprise with Iran is still effective. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Russia hopes to discuss the issue with Iran soon. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Russia submitted a proposal to Iran on building a joint uranium enrichment enterprise in Russia at the end of last December. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The European Union and the United States both indicated that they could accept this compromise plan. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Iran hopes that Russia can continue to revise the original plan. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Kong Quan, spokesman for China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, said on the 7th that even though the IAEA had reported Iran's nuclear issue to the UN Security Council, it had not shifted its responsibility to handle Iran's nuclear issue to the UN Security Council. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Thus, all parties still have to break the stalemate of Iran's nuclear issue within the IAEA's framework. </seg>
<seg id="18"> According to the IAEA resolution, the agency's Director-General ElBaradei will submit a report on Iran's nuclear issue to the UN Security Council in March. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The UN Security Council will make a final decision after evaluating the report. </seg>
<seg id="20"> We believe this resolution is asking Iran to fulfill its obligations and commitments, but it is not transferring the IAEA's responsibility on handling the Iran nuclear issue to the UN Security Council. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Recently, China has been seeking peaceful resolutions to Iran's nuclear problem through diplomatic channels for some time. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Kong Quan said that Zhang Yan, Director-General of China's Department of Arms Control and Disarmament at the Foreign Ministry, had held talks on Iran's nuclear issue with Larijani, Secretary of Iran's Supreme National Security Council and chief negotiator, in Tehran on February 1. </seg>
<seg id="23"> China hopes that Iran will take great stock in the emphasis of the international community and create conditions for a peaceful solution to Iran's nuclear issue. </seg>
<seg id="24"> To solve the Iranian nuclear issue within the IAEA framework serves not only China's interest, but also the interest of all parties concerned. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Therefore, we again call on the parties concerned in the international community not to quit the diplomatic effort that has been conducted on this issue. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="CCTV4_DAILYNEWS_CMN_20060208_145800_256_429.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="E02">
<seg id="1"> Hamas, which is in the process of establishing the new Palestinian autonomous government, officially announced that the Cabinet list of the new government is ready, except for the Prime Minister candidate. </seg>
<seg id="2"> This had caused various speculations on the Prime Minister candidate. </seg>
<seg id="3"> A senior Hamas official revealed to the Associated Press on the 8th that Hamas plans to nominate al-Khudairi, Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Islamic University in Gaza and ((businessman)), as the new Prime Minister of the  autonomous government, but the nomination has not been formally presented to Abbas. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Al-Khudairi, 50, ran in the Palestinian Legislative Council elections as an independent candidate last month with the support of Hamas. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Al-Khudairi never mentioned anything relating to violence or anti-Israel in his public address. </seg>
<seg id="6"> However, he had mentioned that internal reform is needed for Palestine. </seg>
<seg id="7"> A senior delegation from Hamas is currently visiting Cairo to discuss with Egypt the issue of Hamas' establishment of the new Palestinian government. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Khaled Mashaal, a member of the delegation, told the press on the 8th that despite the continuous pressure from the international community and some Arab countries, the Palestinian government led and established by Hamas will not recognize Israel. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Mashaal also issued a warning to Abbas in his statement not to change the structure of the Palestinian leadership without consulting Hamas. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Analysts believe that this was a response to Abbas's plan to appoint Interior Minister Youssef as deputy commander of the Palestinian security forces. </seg>
<seg id="11"> In regard to the establishment of the new Palestinian autonomous government, Mashaal declined to confirm Hamas' plan to name al-Khudairi, Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Islamic University in Gaza and ((businessman)), as the Prime Minister of the government. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Mashaal said, "We have not decided who we will name as Prime Minister." </seg>
<seg id="13"> Before Mashaal reiterated the refusal to recognize Israel, Marzuk, another Hamas political leader, stated during an interview with an Egyptian television station that Hamas will never recognize the legitimacy of Israel, but the new government will keep in touch with Israel in all areas since recognizing Israel and dealing with them are two different things. </seg>
<seg id="14"> Territorial issues have always been a staggering problem in the Israel-Palestinian relationship, despite all the old and recent grudges between the three Hamas Prime Minister candidates and Israel. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Olmert, acting Israeli Prime Minister, said during an interview with Israel's Channel 2 TV on the 7th that Israel has to separate from Palestine through the drawing of permanent borders. </seg>
<seg id="16"> This implied that Israel must withdraw from parts of the West Bank territory. </seg>
<seg id="17"> However, Olmert stressed that Israel will maintain control of the Jewish settlement blocs in the West Bank and the Jordan River Valley, and will retain a united Jerusalem. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="CCTV4_NEWS3_CMN_20060216_075800_208_476.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="E02">
<seg id="1"> Good. Thank you for tuning in to China's News. </seg>
<seg id="2"> The Chinese Consulate General in Karachi confirmed on the 15th that three Chinese engineers and a Pakistani driver were murdered yesterday in Balochistan province in southwestern Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="3"> After learning the news late last night, Chinese President Hu Jintao showed deep concern for the safety of the Chinese engineers in Pakistan. </seg>
<seg id="4"> He instructed the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Chinese embassy and consulates in Pakistan to demand that Pakistan arrest the murderers, to ensure the safety of the Chinese there, and to properly handle the aftermath of the victims. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Hu Jintao also extended his condolences to the Chinese victims and expressed sincere sympathy for the victims' families. </seg>
<seg id="6"> Early this morning, Li Zhaoxing, Chinese Foreign Minister, made an urgent call to his Pakistani counterpart Kasuri, under the instruction of President Hu Jintao. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The Chinese embassy and consulates in Pakistan immediately mobilized an emergency plan, and relevant personnel had already arrived at the scene. </seg>
<seg id="8"> Premier Wen Jiabao had also given instructions to ensure the safety of the Chinese personnel, to properly handle the aftermath, and to request Pakistan to arrest the murderers. </seg>
<seg id="9"> In addition, according to the newest information from the Chinese Consulate General in Karachi, the bodies of the three Chinese had been transported to Karachi early this morning and will be brought back to China on a chartered flight within a few days. </seg>
<seg id="10"> After the attack, the Chinese Consulate General in Karachi immediately dispatched a three-person team to rush to the scene, and transported the bodies of the three Chinese engineers to be placed in a Karachi hospital. </seg>
<seg id="11"> Meanwhile, more than 10 Chinese personnel who work at the same work site with these few people had retreated to Karachi. They are emotionally stable at the moment. </seg>
<seg id="12"> The attack happened in the town of Hub, southeast of Quetta. </seg>
<seg id="13"> On that day, six Chinese engineers who worked at a local cement factory were in a car returning to their residences from their work site. Their car was suddenly stopped by some unidentified gunmen on motorcycles. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The gunmen opened fire with assault rifles, killing three engineers. </seg>
<seg id="15"> After the attack, a tribal militant group named the Baloch Liberation Army claimed responsibility for the shooting. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Pakistan's Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement that night, strongly condemning the attack, calling the incident a terrorist act. </seg>
<seg id="17"> The three Chinese killed were Long Hongbao, Wei Jianping, and Zhao Bin. They were engineers from the Hefei Cement Industry Design and Research Institute of Anhui under the Headquarters of the China National Building Material Group Corporation. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Qin Gang, Spokesman for China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, stated today that Chinese leaders were greatly concerned about the attack on Chinese engineers in Pakistan. They requested Pakistan to ensure the safety of the Chinese personnel there, and to arrest the murderers as soon as possible. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Qin Gang said that Zhang Chunxiang, Chinese Ambassador to Pakistan, had related the relevant situation and lodged negotiations with Pakistani government and army leaders. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Pakistan strongly condemned this barbarous and cruel incident and expressed their condolences to the victims. They also indicated that they will do their utmost to arrest the murderers and will fully coordinate with China in handling the matter. </seg>
<seg id="21"> The Ministry of Foreign Affairs is coordinating relevant departments to arrange to bring back the victims' bodies to China as soon as possible. </seg>
<seg id="22"> The aftermath handling team formed by the victims' work unit, the Hefei Cement Industry Design and Research Institute of Anhui under the Headquarters of the China National Building Material Group Corporation, had left Beijing for Pakistan this morning. </seg>
<seg id="23"> China's Ministry of Commerce had also set up an emergency task force after the incident. </seg>
