<seg id="53"> In the end, one of the individuals was tragically killed in the rescue operation. </seg>
<seg id="54"> Also, three engineers were killed in a bomb attack in Gwador in May of the same year. </seg>
<seg id="55"> Let's take a look back. </seg>
<seg id="56"> On May 3, 2004, in the port of Gwador in the south of the Pakistani province of Balochistan, a vehicle carrying twelve Chinese headed toward a worksite at the port was hit by a car bomb attack. </seg>
<seg id="57"> As a result, three Chinese engineers were killed and nine individuals were injured. </seg>
<seg id="58"> Local armed separatists and tribal militants are believed to have launched the attack. </seg>
<seg id="59"> On October 9 of the same year, two Chinese engineers were kidnapped by armed militants in the area of South Waziristan in the border region between Pakistan and Afghanistan. </seg>
<seg id="60"> A short while after, one engineer was fatally shot as Pakistani troops were rescuing the hostages. </seg>
<seg id="61"> However, it is believed that the hostage-taking was carried out by armed militants linked to Al Qaeda and not armed separatists. </seg>
<seg id="62"> Because China has close economic ties with Pakistan and participates in infrastructure projects in that country, several Chinese engineers work there. </seg>
<seg id="63"> On the other hand, there are also armed tribal groups in Pakistan that accuse the government of plundering their natural resources. </seg>
<seg id="64"> This has resulted in Chinese becoming the victims of attacks or kidnappings on several occasions. </seg>
<seg id="65"> This is a news brief by Phoenix Satellite Television. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="PHOENIX_GOODMORNCN_CMN_20060215_185801_955_1163.qrtr" genre="broadcast_news" sysid="E03">
<seg id="1"> Let's take a look at some news items from  Japan. </seg>
<seg id="2"> Recently, Japan's political arena produced some rather sensational news. </seg>
<seg id="3"> That is, Tsuneo Watanabe, chairman of one of Japan's leading papers, the Yomiuri Shimbun, he ordered Yomiuri Shimbun to publish some articles ...eh ... that oppose Koizumi's visit to the Yasukuni Shrine, marking Yomiuri Shimbun's shift to a stand against Koizumi's visit to Yasukuni Shrine. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Eh ... so ... this Tsuneo Watanabe ..., in the speech he made a few days ago, he also lashed out at Koizumi ..., saying that he is ignorant and has no historical and cultural knowledge. </seg>
<seg id="5"> At the same time, he commented that visiting Yasukuni Shrine was just like paying tribute to Hitler and said that, in so doing, Koizumi ... eh ... had caused China and South Korea to ... eh ... regard Japan as a very dangerous country. This will bring endless troubles. </seg>
<seg id="6"> So why has Tsuneo Watanabe's attitude caused such a  repercussion? </seg>
<seg id="7"> In fact, he is very influential in political circles and has always been a major behind-the-scenes operator. </seg>
<seg id="8"> And he used to be a very rightist figure. </seg>
<seg id="9"> It should be said that he has always been a supporter of the hawks and strongly advocated revision of the constitution. </seg>
<seg id="10"> But, now, ... well ... this is really a major turn-around. </seg>
<seg id="11"> He turned his gun and ... eh ... opened fire  on Koizumi, adopting an attitude of opposition. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Actually, in 2004, when Koizumi was being criticized for visiting Yasukuni Shrine, this Tsuneo Watanabe ... he ... eh ... he said that he supported it and wanted Koizumi to withstand the pressure. </seg>
<seg id="13"> Recently, however, he made a speech, saying: "I am over 80 years old and don't have many days left." </seg>
<seg id="14"> So, he now stands up to make a high-profile speech with a very opposing attitude. </seg>
<seg id="15"> Such a turnaround of course produced a significant impact on the entire Japanese society. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Just as Tsuneo Watanabe himself put it, he said: "I am convinced that I have the strength to control and change the direction of the political winds." </seg>
<seg id="17"> And he also said that he would put up a desperate resistance if the government pressured Yomiuri Shimbun with respect to its freedom of speech or its ability to interview. </seg>
<seg id="18"> So, what has the situation come to now? </seg>
<seg id="19"> Well, Japan's largest newspaper, Yomiuri Shimbun, and the second largest newspaper, Asahi Shimbu...eh, these two leading newspapers have started to team up in opposition to Koizumi's visit to Yasukuni Shrine. </seg>
<seg id="20"> Originally, the two papers were opponents, but after the two chairmen met, they were able to reach agreement on this issue at least. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Therefore, they have now launched a campaign of considerable scale to criticize Koizumi. You can say that they have formed an ideal combination. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Actually, these two large newspapers have great sway over mainstream public opinion in Japan. </seg>
<seg id="23"> In a separate development, let's look at the meeting of the Japanese parliament. At a recent meeting, two candidates favored to succeed Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi made the same type of remarks. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Who were the two? </seg>
<seg id="25"> One was Chief Cabinet Secretary Shinzo Abe and the other was Minister for Foreign Affairs Taro Aso, who of late has frequently made astonishing remarks. </seg>
<seg id="26"> What did the two say? </seg>
<seg id="27"> They said that Japanese war criminals of the Second World War were not criminals. </seg>
<seg id="28"> What they mean is ... eh ... that, they claimed that these criminals ... it was the intention of the international court to convict them. </seg>
<seg id="29"> But, in Japan, according to international laws ... they were citing the domestic laws of Japan ... eh ... the war criminals ... did not break the domestic laws of Japan. </seg>
<seg id="30"> So, they think that, in Japan, World War II criminals should not be regarded as criminals. </seg>
<seg id="31"> This Shinzo Abe ... he also mentioned that Japan now ... eh ... should take the whole world into account, develop relations with the United States and develop commercial and trade relations with some East Asian countries, and, furthermore, it should also try to develop closer ties with India rather than always focus on China. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_LNTS_14974749cb4b6f49_CMN_20060216_084900" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E03">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Chance at the Championship, But It's Not a Sure Thing </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Love life, love Lu Neng </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> The China Football Association Super League is set for some fierce battles. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Luneng Taishan is getting combat-ready for the new season with the championship in mind. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Hot competitions will be triggered between the Dalian, Shandong and Shanghai teams, the three strongest competitors for the championship. </seg>
<seg id="6"> In the end, who will win the championship? </seg>
<seg id="7"> Based on an analysis of their strengths, Taishan has a very good chance to become champion, but it is by no means a sure thing. </seg>
<seg id="8"> First of all, the new team members have not had long enough to get worked in. </seg>
<seg id="9"> Taishan lost at four major events last year. </seg>
<seg id="10"> This year, Taishan recruited two players from the national team--Li Leilei and Wang Liang. With the addition of two foreign players soon afterwards, it is safe to say that the team will be stronger. </seg>
<seg id="11"> But because the national football team is preparing for matches with Palestine and Iraq, there no way to say how well the two players from the national team will integrate. </seg>
<seg id="12"> By the time they return to the club, league matches will be set to begin. </seg>
<seg id="13"> That is why integration has become the most significant issue Taishan is facing. </seg>
<seg id="14"> In my view, the national-team players can be used as backups in the first few rounds of league matches. </seg>
<seg id="15"> First, team integration can be achieved using the in-game training. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Second, the national-team players who have just played group matches with the national team can use the lull to rest up. </seg>
<seg id="17"> After a few rounds, when the "knife is well sharpened', it will not be too late for them to play top spots. </seg>
<seg id="18"> In addition, the defense has some weaknesses. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Last year, Taishan's fans had some unfavorable things to say about the team's defense. </seg>
<seg id="20"> This year, the defense will have improved with the recruitment of Li Leilei. But it's still not the time to sit back and relax. </seg>
<seg id="21"> There's still the problem of sluggish turnaround at the center back position, and the substitutes for this position are either too old or lacking in experience. </seg>
<seg id="22"> If performance at the center back position can be stabilized, Taishan will gain some momentum on the road to becoming champion. </seg>
<seg id="23"> In my opinion, they might as well use Ren Yongshun, who is strong physically. Although he lacks experience, he should be put to work this year so as to be ready in the future. </seg>
<seg id="24"> In addition, Gao Yao can play center back as well. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Taishan has quite a few players who can play defending midfield, such as Cui Peng and Hai Bing. </seg>
<seg id="26"> Gao Yao is physically very strong and a ferocious interceptor. He should be able to handle the center back position. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Another question is whether the foreign recruits can adjust. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Taishan has been plagued by problems with foreign recruits. </seg>
<seg id="29"> The performance of Daniel [Daniel Danciulescu] last year was far from stellar. </seg>
<seg id="30"> We know that this year's selection of foreign players has not yet been finalized. </seg>
<seg id="31"> I think that apart from bringing in an excellent striker, a true left-footed midfielder should also be recruited this year. </seg>
<seg id="32"> Except for Xing Rui, who played for the team a few years ago, Taishan has not had a true left-footed player with good skills. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Although players like Cui Peng and other can play the position, a truly competent left half back would be greatly preferred to fill-in. </seg>
<seg id="34"> If these three issues can be solved, Taishan's road to the championship should be somewhat smoother. </seg>
<seg id="35"> As a Shandong football fan, I'm really hoping Taishan can win the championship this year. </seg>
<seg id="36"> But to be frank, with things looking like they do in the championships this year, Taishan has a good chance, but it is far from a sure thing. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_brandvista_4a454bf36d4bd92a_CMN_20060210_062400" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E03">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> The Incorporation of Batey Ads into JWT's Network: Is It Too Late to Say Happy New Year? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  BrandVista Post: </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> Hello, everybody. </seg>
<seg id="4"> Once again, the Chinese New Year has flown by and those who combined their vacation time with their New Year's holiday are now returning to their jobs. </seg>
<seg id="5"> We wish all our friends a happy New Year, if it is not too late to say Happy New Year. </seg>
<seg id="6"> We spoke recently at a cafe with NPLCN. He talked about present-day Brandvista. </seg>
<seg id="7"> The appearance of the website has improved greatly. </seg>
<seg id="8"> The content is well structured. </seg>
<seg id="9"> What pleases him most is the Discuz-powered community BBS, which has undergone a thorough revamping. </seg>
<seg id="10"> In regards to the community, I must thank one person. </seg>
<seg id="11"> That is, Mr. Li Mingshun, general manager of Discuz Beijing. </seg>
<seg id="12"> If you search for his name in Google, you will get a slew of hits. </seg>
<seg id="13"> You probably know that he was previously with Sina. He later started his own business, setting up an Internet advertisement exchange platform for SMEs that was similar to the overseas website Adbrite.com. </seg>
<seg id="14"> We discussed it with him at the time on MSN. What he said, in general, was that: Brandvista felt that the development of many industries in China depended on the expansion of the private economy and SMEs. </seg>
<seg id="15"> And currently, in the Chinese market, this situation does not give reason for optimism. </seg>
<seg id="16"> So SME's in creative industries and similar services are unable to provide consultation to any significant extent. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Collecting high fees to advance one's own development in the end leads to a discouraging cycle. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Later, he came to Discuz. </seg>
<seg id="19"> Discuz is an outstanding forum program powered by PHP and MySQL. </seg>
<seg id="20"> With the help of Ramboo, a technical engineer from Beijing, Brandvista finally saw the light of day once again and hit the stage with matchless freshness. </seg>
<seg id="21"> The feedback was very good. </seg>
<seg id="22"> The interface was neat and friendly. </seg>
<seg id="23"> It was also very fast. </seg>
<seg id="24"> With the neat interface, writing a few words that moved me and inspired others, exchanging tidbits about work and life with friends from the same industry that shared the same pursuits, I began to find that this was a pleasure. </seg>
<seg id="25"> Thank you Discuz! </seg>
<seg id="26"> Recently, there has been a lot of news from the advertising industry. </seg>
<seg id="27"> Starting in January, the WTO system of openness in the ad industry began to be implemented. </seg>
<seg id="28"> Large foreign companies have been arriving one after another. Small foreign companies are sharpening their sword for battle. It seems to be a scene of prosperity. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Batey Ads, which rose to prominence in Singapore, has been having many difficulties. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Having lost a string of big clients and having suffered repeated setbacks in its development in mainland China, Martin Boase finally took a little time from a lawsuit in Italy to think about shuffling things around. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Batey Ads will merge into JWT's network, keeping its own brandname and being managed by JWT. </seg>
<seg id="32"> However, at the same time, there were also rumors that Bates and 141 Network would merge into the Ogilvy and Mather system and be managed by the Ogilvy and Mather network. </seg>
<seg id="33"> Even if 141 had already given its report to Ogilvy and Mather prior to that, having Ted Bates get payback against Ogilvy and Mather is also a interesting matter. </seg>
<seg id="34"> During the Spring Festival, several articles on the website were updated. We won't go into each one here. </seg>
<seg id="35"> Everybody can go to the website to take a look when they have time. </seg>
<seg id="36"> At the same time, friends who still haven't entered the new forum can, with a few extra clicks of a mouse, enter into Brandvista's completely new community. </seg>
<seg id="37"> You can get a feel for the environment, get to know the atmosphere and contribute a few words. </seg>
<seg id="38"> We hope you will find pleasure in finding the group. </seg>
<seg id="39"> We wish all friends a pleasant mood. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Goodbye. </seg>
<seg id="41"> Brandvista, Xiaorong </seg>
<seg id="42"> http://www.brandvista.com </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_fwcc_f363bceb6bd8a406_CMN_20060215_082900" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E03">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> A Mother Ten Years in the Past </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Helen Li </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> I saw this article and decided to share it with you; </seg>
<seg id="4"> This is not a momentary impulse, but rather a warm kindheartedness that has long existed in the heart. </seg>
<seg id="5"> I asked myself what I would do if it were me. </seg>
<seg id="6"> The answer is very clear. I would way, "You have the wrong number" and hang up the telephone. </seg>
<seg id="7"> I've been thinking all this year about how one can actually help someone. </seg>
<seg id="8"> I have already given up on actions such as donating money or goods. </seg>
<seg id="9"> A couple days ago a friend said, "I already have no spare time to take care of myself. As for helping people, the heart is there by the means are not." </seg>
<seg id="10"> Have a nice day :) </seg>
<seg id="11"> Helen </seg>
<seg id="12"> A Mother Ten Years in the Past </seg>
<seg id="13"> It was a day ten years ago. The teacher was using the lunch break to nap at home, when suddenly the telephone rang. </seg>
<seg id="14"> She answered and heard an unfamiliar rough voice from the receiver: "Your child stole a book and we caught her. Come over right away!" </seg>
<seg id="15"> The crying of a little girl could also be heard though the receiver, as well as the sound of somebody nearby scolding her. </seg>
<seg id="16"> She turned her head to look at her only daughter watching the television and then immediately understood what was happening. </seg>
<seg id="17"> Clearly, a little girl had been caught by a store clerk stealing a book and did not want her family to find out, so she dialed a number at random and happened to call there. </seg>
<seg id="18"> Of course, she could hang up and forget about it, or even reprimand the party on the other line, </seg>
<seg id="19"> because this affair had absolutely nothing to do with her. </seg>
<seg id="20"> But she was a teacher, and it could be that it was one of her students. </seg>
<seg id="21"> Through the telephone, she could roughly imagine that the little girl who had made a mistake on the spur of the moment was surely terrified, since she was facing what could be life's most frightening circumstance. </seg>
<seg id="22"> After hesitating a moment, a thought suddenly came to her mind. Yes, she would do it. </seg>
<seg id="23"> Thereupon, after asking the bookstore's address, she rushed over there. </seg>
<seg id="24"> Just as she had anticipated, standing in the bookstore was a little girl with a face full of tears. </seg>
<seg id="25"> The adults beside her were ferociously and loudly scolding her. </seg>
<seg id="26"> She instantly rushed forward and gathered the pitiful little girl into her arms, then turned toward the nearby store clerk and said: "Whatever you have to say you can say to me. You shouldn't frighten children." </seg>
<seg id="27"> During the muttering of the somewhat unwilling store clerk, she paid the fine of less than one hundred yuan and then, with the little girl in hand, walked out of the store where she could see clearly the face overwhelmed by panic and tears. </seg>
<seg id="28"> She smiled and returned home with the little girl where she tidied her up without asking anything, then let the little girl leave, </seg>
<seg id="29"> As the little girl was about to go, she also made a point of urging, "If you want to read a book, then come here to Auntie's house. There are lots of books here.' </seg>
<seg id="30"> The still badly shaken little girl looked are her deeply for a moment, then dashed off, after which she never came back. </seg>
<seg id="31"> Time rushed by like running water. Imperceptibly, ten years went by in a flash. </seg>
<seg id="32"> She had forgotten the incident, still living there as before, she led a calm and peaceful life. </seg>
<seg id="33"> One afternoon, there was a knocking on the outside door. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Opening the door to her apartment, she saw a pretty young woman she did not know. The girl was smiling broadly and in her hands she held a stack of presents. </seg>
<seg id="35"> "Who are you looking for?" </seg>
<seg id="36"> she asked with uncertainty. </seg>
<seg id="37"> The young girl excitedly gave a long explanation. </seg>
<seg id="38"> To her surprise, from the unfamiliar young lady's story she suddenly realized that the young woman was actually the little girl from that year. Ten years later, she had graduated from university without difficulty and had now come especially to call on her. </seg>
<seg id="39"> The young woman's eyes glistened with tears as she said in a gentle voice: "Although I still don't understand even today why you were willing to pass yourself off as my mother and come to my rescue, but for the last ten years I had a constant feeling that I wanted to cry out 'Mother' to you." </seg>
<seg id="40"> The teacher's eyes started to cloud over as well. </seg>
<seg id="41"> Somewhat curious, she asked: "If I hadn't helped you that day, what would have been the result?" </seg>
<seg id="42"> The young woman's face instantly darkened and she lightly shook her head, saying: "I'm not sure. Maybe I would have gone on doing stupid things, or I might even have died." </seg>
<seg id="43"> A violent shiver went through the teacher's heart, then she rejoiced to  herself. </seg>
<seg id="44"> The impetuous decision that she had made back then had unexpectedly had such an influence on a person's entire life. </seg>
<seg id="45"> Looking at the happy smile on the young woman's face, she also began to smile. </seg>
<poster>
<seg id="46"> <POSTER>  zhang xiwen </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="47"> While the world is full of lies and cheating that fill the air like junk messages, Buddha says, "Who would enter hell but I would enter it..." </seg>
<seg id="48"> Whoever is willing to do that, I congratulate him. He will achieve Buddhahood sooner. </seg>
<seg id="49"> Human nature is good at the outset. </seg>
<seg id="50"> Everybody has a compassionate heart. </seg>
<seg id="51"> The world is going to the dogs and people's hearts have changed. </seg>
<seg id="52"> Perhaps only by abandoning one's own Buddha can one do a little good. </seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="groups.google.com_goodarticles_90837c9a1fbe858e_CMN_20060214_082900" genre="newsgroup" sysid="E03">
<hl>
<seg id="1"> <HEADLINE> Military Observation: How Long Can Iran Hold Out under US Air Attacks? </seg>
</hl>
<poster>
<seg id="2"> <POSTER>  Yun Feiquan </seg>
</poster>
<seg id="3"> If we describe conventional war of attrition as causing the opponent to bleed to death, then from the outset modern warfare consists of shooting a gun toward the opponent's head in order to render him a "vegetable" even before there is time to bleed. </seg>
<seg id="4"> The disparity between the military capabilities of Iran and the US is not one of quantity, but rather in the understanding of modern war. </seg>
<seg id="5"> Iran, which fought a victorless eight-year war with Iraq, seems not yet to have understood the true significance of modern hi-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="6"> Following an analysis of US military deployments, Britain's "International Intelligence--Commentary" recently said that the US military is carrying out preparations to launch a large scale air assault on Iran...... </seg>
<seg id="7"> The current status of Iran's air force is cause for concern. </seg>
<seg id="8"> The present situation of Iran's air force is quite similar to that of Iraq's air force prior to the 2003 war. </seg>
<seg id="9"> The country does not possess the capacity to research and develop modern weapons on its own and is also under an arms embargo imposed by the west. </seg>
<seg id="10"> Once war breaks out, it is uncertain whether the antiquated planes in Iran's air force will be able to take to the air to engage US forces. </seg>
<seg id="11"> At present, Iran's air-defense system consists primarily of an air force belonging to Iran's regular forces, the land-based air-defense force and the air-defense capacity of the revolutionary guard. </seg>
<seg id="12"> Of these, Iran's air force presently has a manpower of 50,000 and more than 300 aircraft of various models. </seg>
<seg id="13"> The most important aircraft models include US-manufactured F-4 Phantoms, F5 Tigers, F-14 Tomcats and Russian-manufactured Mig-29s. </seg>
<seg id="14"> The land-based air-defense force is primarily equipped with surface-to-air missiles of the US-manufactured Hawk series and the British Rapier series, as well as a portion belong to the Russian-manufactured SAM series. </seg>
<seg id="15"> With regards to the current status of Iran's air-defense strength,  analysis by individuals such as the US military expert Harold Hutchison and  military expert [Hela Muqixin] of the [Russian Political and Military Research Institute] indicates that, viewed from the present situation, there are still holes in Iran's air-defense capabilities and air-defense system. </seg>
<seg id="16"> Hutchison says that with respect to overall capabilities, Iran's air force simply is not on the same level as the US air force. </seg>
<seg id="17"> A large number of the US-manufactured jetfighters that Iran is equipped with cannot be used because of a lack of spare parts and upgrading. </seg>
<seg id="18"> The F-14 fighter was once the trump card of Iran's air force, but today there are only ten or so that are able to fly. </seg>
<seg id="19"> The dependability in actual combat of the AIM-54 Phoenix missiles they carry, known for their ultra-long distance attack capabilities, is also doubtful. </seg>
<seg id="20"> [Hela Muqixin] points out however that the air-defense missile systems provided to Iran by the US in the 1970s and 1980s have lost their warfare capabilities because of a lack of spare parts. </seg>
<seg id="21"> In addition, the other non-systematic air-defense weapons obtained from Russia and other countries are simply incapable of countering US forces possessing powerful electromagnetic countermeasure capabilities. </seg>
<seg id="22"> Scraping Together a Military Affects Battle Capability </seg>
<seg id="23"> Clearly, Iran's government is also aware that its fate in a conflict depends upon whether it can defend the sky above and it has been carrying out eleventh-hour preparations by scraping together whatever it can find in order to build up its air-defense system. </seg>
<seg id="24"> At present, its methods can be summarized into two devices: </seg>
<seg id="25"> The first is an all-out effort to conceal key nuclear facilities and beef up their defense capabilities. </seg>
<seg id="26"> According to a report in the British newspaper The Times, Iran has hidden the Natanz Nuclear Facility, the Isfahan Uranium Enrichment Center and other core components of their nuclear facilities eighteen meters underground and added a two-meter thick concrete protection shell. </seg>
<seg id="27"> But the US military is one step ahead. As early as the 1991 Persian Gulf War, it saw the effectiveness of underground bunkers in anti-aircraft defense and rushed to develop various types of earth-penetrating bombs. </seg>
<seg id="28"> After ten years of focused research, the US military has a full complement of strategies and weapons to counter reinforced underground bunkers. </seg>
<seg id="29"> Iran has recently also bought a large amount of advanced air-defense weapons from Russia. </seg>
<seg id="30"> Since the end of last year, Iran's government has reached a series of agreements with Russia to purchase Pechora-2A air defense missile systems as well as 29 Tor-M1 air-defense missile systems valued at US$700m. </seg>
<seg id="31"> However, modern warfare is a contest of system against system. </seg>
<seg id="32"> The various air-attack weapons of the US military have all been developed by the country itself for its own benefit and, through many years of perfectioning in actual combat, they have been molded into an impressive war machine. </seg>
<seg id="33"> On the other hand, Iran's "up-to-date weapons" have been scraped together from other countries. Whether or not they can be made combat effective in such a short time is still in question. </seg>
<seg id="34"> Iran's Lags Behind Not Only in Weapons </seg>
<seg id="35"> The concept of "air-land battle" was first raised in "Operations", published by the US military in 1982. It stresses reliance on strength in the air to carry out attacks against the enemy's strategically valuable targets. This paralyses the other side's command systems at the start of the war and turns the enemy's conventional forces, even if they are superior, into a "slab of meat on a cutting board." </seg>
<seg id="36"> In the 1991 Persian Gulf War, the 1999 Kosovo War and the 2003 Iraq War, the US military did not concern itself with how many planes the opponent had, but rather the range of its own Tomahawk cruise missiles. </seg>
<seg id="37"> Even if Iran's government has prepared for a possible air attack and has begun to take steps to reinforce its air-defense capabilities, Iran, which fought to a stalemate in an eight-year war with Iraq, seems not to have fully understood the true meaning of modern hi-tech warfare. </seg>
<seg id="38"> With the progress of the US military's military transformation in recent years, the US military's air-attack operations are completely different from the carpet bombing of the Vietnam War and instead rely on full-depth air assaults with various hi-tech weapons and modern information technology. </seg>
<seg id="39"> Faced with this kind of air assault, how long Iran's land-based air defense systems can hold out is an unknown. </seg>
<seg id="40"> Source: CRI Online- "World News Journal" </seg>
